# 🧠 Why It’s Slow

Your pipeline currently does:

For each image:

1. Read image (disk I/O)
2. Resize
3. Face detection (heavy)
4. Generate embedding (heavy)
5. Normalize
6. Store in DB
7. Generate thumbnail
8. Later → DBSCAN clustering
9. FAISS indexing

If average time per image = 1.2 sec
232 × 1.2 = ~278 seconds (4–5 minutes)

That’s normal for CPU.

---

# 🚨 Biggest Bottlenecks

### 🔴 1. InsightFace detection on CPU

This is the slowest part.

### 🔴 2. Large images (4000px wedding photos)

Even if resized, loading takes time.

### 🔴 3. DBSCAN clustering

O(n²) complexity.

### 🔴 4. Saving embeddings one-by-one in DB

---

# 🚀 How To Make It 3–5x Faster

We optimize in layers.

---

# ✅ 1️⃣ Reduce Image Size More Aggressively

Currently you resize only if > 1400px.

Change this:

```python
MAX_DIM = 1400
```

To:

```python
MAX_DIM = 900
```

Even:

```python
MAX_DIM = 800
```

Face detection works fine at 800px.

This alone can reduce processing time 40–50%.

---

# ✅ 2️⃣ Disable Thumbnail Generation During Processing

Thumbnail generation inside loop slows it a lot.

Temporarily comment this:

```python
create_thumbnail(event_id, image_name)
```

You can generate thumbnails later lazily when requested.

This saves significant time.

---

# ✅ 3️⃣ Batch Insert Instead of db.add() Per Face

Currently you do:

```python
db.add(db_cluster)
db.flush()
```

inside loop.

That’s slow.

Instead:

```python
clusters_to_add = []

for ...
    clusters_to_add.append(db_cluster)

db.bulk_save_objects(clusters_to_add)
db.commit()
```

Much faster.

---

# ✅ 4️⃣ Skip DBSCAN Completely (Huge Gain)

This is big.

Instead of:

```
Collect all embeddings
Run DBSCAN
Then store clusters
```

You can:

* Directly assign cluster using FAISS nearest neighbors
* Or skip clustering entirely for MVP

DBSCAN on 500+ embeddings is slow.

If you skip DBSCAN → processing becomes 3x faster.

---

